{"title_page": "Historical Vaikundar", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2018}}\n[[File:Vaikundar---Historical-vs-Religious.png|thumb|200px|[[Vaikundar]] : Historical vs Spiritual views]]\n'''Historical Vaikundar''' (1809\u20131851) refers to the life and teachings of [[Ayya Vaikundar]], as known in [[Akilathirattu Ammanai]], being reconstructed from a historical perspective with reference to various historical sources in contrast to the mythological [[Akilam]]ic views. Though few events referred to in the mythology have yet to be validated historically, many key events mentioned in [[Akilam]] were acknowledged  by  other contemporary  sources.\n\nAyya Vaikundar was the first<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.hindu.com/2004/08/29/stories/2004082904420400.htm|title= The Hindu |accessdate=7 February 2007 |format= The Sree Narayana effect|work=Credit to reformers: \"The first of the social revolutionaries was Vaikunta Swami (1809\u20131851).\" |location=Chennai, India |date=29 August 2004| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070305164930/http://www.hindu.com/2004/08/29/stories/2004082904420400.htm| archivedate= 5 March 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> to succeed as a social reformer<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.hindu.com/2006/03/19/stories/2006031900640200.htm|title= The Hindu|accessdate=7 February 2007 |format= `Communalism an important factor in politics'|work=Great reformers|location=Chennai, India|date=19 March 2006| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070111132234/http://www.hindu.com/2006/03/19/stories/2006031900640200.htm| archivedate= 11 January 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.hindu.com/2004/07/06/stories/2004070612160300.htm|title= The Hindu \u2013 India's National Newspaper|accessdate=16 September 2007 |format= Around the City|work=AIR programme|location=Chennai, India|date=6 July 2004}} This link about a programme by '[[All India Radio]]' includes [[Ayya Vaikundar]] as a [[Social reformer]].</ref> in launching political struggle,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.hindu.com/cp/2007/09/28/stories/2007092850300800.htm|title= The Hindu \u2013 India's National Newspaper|accessdate=23 January 2008 |format= Stargazing|work=Ayya's story|location=Chennai, India|date=28 September 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080214111454/http://www.hindu.com/cp/2007/09/28/stories/2007092850300800.htm| archivedate= 14 February 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> social renaissance<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.education.kerala.gov.in/englishmedium/historyeng/chapter9.pdf|title= www.education.kerala.gov.in|accessdate= 23 January 2008|format= Towards Modern Kerala|work= 10th Standard Text Book, Chapter 9, p. 101.|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081217193847/http://www.education.kerala.gov.in/englishmedium/historyeng/chapter9.pdf|archivedate= 17 December 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dinamalar.com/2008MAR03/general_tn7.asp |title=www.dinamalar.com |accessdate=3 May 2008 |format=Silently spreading Love-flag |work=Dinamalar (Leading Tamil Daily), 3 March 2008. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202150511/http://dinamalar.com/2008MAR03/general_tn7.asp |archivedate=2 December 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tnuniv.ac.in/tansche/reports/History%20Education%20in%20the%2021st%20Century.pdf |title=www.tnuniv.ac.in |accessdate=16 September 2007 |format=Tamil Nadu State Council for Higher Education, Social and Cultural History of Tamil Nadu from 1529 to Present day |work=Reform Movements and National Movement, p. 27 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071129185218/http://www.tnuniv.ac.in/tansche/reports/History%20Education%20in%20the%2021st%20Century.pdf |archivedate=29 November 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> as well as religious reformation<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdu.ac.in/cb-ug-his.pdf |title=History of Tamil Nadu from 1800 AD to the Present Day |accessdate=23 January 2008 |format=Bharathidasan University |work=B.A. History \u2013 Course Structure under CBCS, Core Course \u2013 V, p. 9. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071129185219/http://www.bdu.ac.in/cb-ug-his.pdf |archivedate=29 November 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdu.ac.in/cb-pg-his.pdf |title=www.bdu.ac.in |accessdate=7 February 2007 |format=SOCIAL REFORMERS OF MODERN INDIA |work=Unit IV |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051128094048/http://www.bdu.ac.in/cb-pg-his.pdf |archivedate=28 November 2005 }}</ref> Vaikundar was the pioneer of the social revolutionaries of south India<ref>M. Ilanchezhiyan, ''Pandiyarkula Nadrakal Kulamurai Kilathal'', p. 197.</ref> and Kerala.<ref name = \"Sreedharamenon\"/> Research scholars regard Vaikundar as a teacher, healer and also a miracle worker.<ref>George D. Chryssides, ''Historical dictionary of new religious movements'', (Publisher: Lanham, Md., Scarecrow Press) 2012, Page 48, Ayyavazhi.</ref> He was also said to be the forerunner of all social reformers of India.<ref name= \"Immanuel:First Reform Movement\">Immanuel, ''Kanniyakumari: Aspects and Architects'', Chapter 11, pp. 115\u2013116.</ref>  He was in the forefront of movements for Human Rights and Social Equality.<ref name= \"Immanuel:First Reform Movement\" /> His teachings also effected many social changes in southern India,<ref>R. Ponnu, ''Vaikunda Swamigal Ore Avataram'', p. 152</ref> resulting in the emergence of a series of social and [[self-respect movement]]s such as ''Upper cloth agitation'',<ref name = \"Sreedharamenon\">A. Sreedhara Menon, ''A Survey of Kerala History'', p. 314</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/article1064574.ece|title= The Hindu|accessdate=3 March 2011 |format= Jayalalithaa to visit Kanyakumari tomorrow|work=' \"He (Vaikundar) spearheaded the thol seelai struggle...\" ' 3 March 2011.}}</ref> [[Temple Entry Proclamation|Temple entry agitation]] and other movements including those of [[Narayana Guru]],<ref name= \"Selvister:First Reform Movement\" >Selvister Ponnumuthan, (1996), ''The spirituality of basic ecclesial communities in the socio-religious context of Trivandrum/Kerala, India'', {{ISBN|88-7652-721-4}}, Editrice Pontificia Universit\u00e0 Gregoriana, pp. 77\u201378</ref> [[Chattampi Swamikal]], [[Arutprakasa Vallalar Chidambaram Ramalinga Swamigal|Vallalar]]<ref name= \"Ponnu:First Reform Movement\" >R. Ponnu, ''Vaikunda swamigal Ore Avataram'', p. 178.</ref> and [[Ayyankali]].\n\n==Early life==\n\nThe year as well as the exact date of birth of Vaikundar is a matter of conflict.  Various historians place the year of birth as 1809 C.E while as few other sources placed his birth in 1808 C.E. Akilam did not mention any direct reference to the date. But by the time he was taken to [[Tiruchendur]] for being cured after he fall sick he was at his 24, for which the exact date is mentioned in Akilam as 20th Masi 1008 M.E which falls on 4 March 1833. The date of birth too is subject to greater conflict. Historians predict various dates from 12 March to 19 April. He has born as the second son to ''Ponnumadan - Veyilal couple''.\n\nThe parents<ref name=vsoa>{{cite book|last1=Ponnu|first1=Ira|title=Vaikunda Swamigal Ore Avatarm|date=2002|publisher=Ram Publishers|location=Madurai|page=52|edition=First}}</ref> and the villagers<ref name=avpv>{{cite book|last1=Amalan|first1=N|title=Ayya Vaikundar Punitha Varalaru|date=2001|publisher=Akilam Publishers|location=Swamithope|page=40|edition=First}}</ref> witnessed some spiritual significance<ref name=Ponnu>{{cite book|last1=Ponnu|first1=R|title=Sri Vaikunda Swamigal and The Struggle for Social Equality in South India|date=2000|publisher=Ram Publishers|location=Madurai|pages=40\u201341|edition=First}}</ref> in the face of the child. A naming ceremony was conducted and the name ''Mudisoodum Perumal (Lord Vishnu with Crown)'' was suggested by the elders and was accepted by others. Since people of lower castes are not allowed to use the names of God or [[Travancore royal family|Rulers]] the upper classes opposed the move<ref name=rasa>{{cite book|last1=Patrick|first1=G|title=Religion and Subaltern Agency|date=2003|publisher=University of Madras|location=Chennai|page=77}}</ref> and demanded an immediate name change.{{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=41}}Fearing the oppression the child was renamed ''Muthukutty''. There are various accounts as to who suggested the name. While few historians claim that the name Muthukutty, which tones prosaical, was suggested by the officials, others argued that though some officials from the administration were against the name '' \u2018Mudisoodum Perumal\u2019 '', they never suggested this alternative. There is another account that while the parents was seeking admission to the child for schooling in a traditional Schools known as ''Thinnai Palli'' the teacher refused to enrol the child with the name and he himself changed the name to Muthukutty.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Vivekanandan|first1=Siva|title=Ayya Vaikundar Vazhvum Vazhibadum|date=2003|publisher=Kavya|location=Chennai|page=78|edition=First}}</ref> Another narration is that the [[Kingdom of Travancore|King of Travancore]], through his Umbrella bearer, Poovandar, directly ordered to change the name which includes the suffix \u2018Perumal\u2019 (Vishnu) to Muthukutty. {{sfn|Amalan|2001|p=8}} Other accounts speculates that the villagers themselves adopted the name as per the existing norms<ref name=\"rasa\" /> as the lower castes of the [[Travancore]] has to use differential language and different set of names to signify their differential social status from the upper classes.{{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=85}}\n\nThough he disliked [[rituals]] and practices {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=42}} he was very religious {{sfn|Amalan|2001|p=6}} and prefers simple worship. {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=42}} He was also very revolutionary in his thoughts, idea and acts right from his childhood. {{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=55}} He was a staunch devotee of Lord Vishnu as he had set a pedestal{{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=55}} and offers regular prayers for [[Vishnu]] at his residence. He  use to meditate regularly during evenings at [[Marunthuvazh Malai]].{{sfn|Amalan|2001|p=6}} He well versed in various ancient arts including [[martial art]]s, {{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=55}} he appears as a multifaceted personality. {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=42}} He was also said to be a very good orator. {{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=55}} Though it is not clear whether he advocated a unified society and supported intermingling of various castes and promoted inter-caste marriages. But he strongly propagated for a society totally free from caste discrimination and also worked for the betterment of the downtrodden. {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=42}} He was intensely against the oppressive treatment of the lower classes. {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=43}}\n\n==Transformation==\n\nAt the age of 17 he married <ref name=Malar>{{cite book|last1=Umai Thanu|first1=C|last2=Kasi Udhayam|first2=P|title=Bhagavan Vaikunda Swamigal Punitha Varalaru|date=2003|publisher=Dinamalar|location=Chennai|pages=65, 66|edition=Second}}</ref> a women Thirumalammal of Puviyoor, Agastheeswaram,{{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=42}} who was left alone by her husband. There is also a view that they never get married and that the women only came to serve him in his activities .{{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=86}} He continued his early life as a [[Palmyra]] Climber <ref name=Mateer>{{cite book|last1=Mateer|first1=Samuel|title=The Land of charity: a descriptive account of Travancore and its people|date=1871|publisher=Asian Educational Services|location=New Delhi|isbn=81-206-0319-2|page=222}}</ref> and as an Agricultural labourer. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=78}} At the age of 22 he fall ill.\n\nThere is another narrative that at his age of 16,{{sfn|Amalan|2000|pp=15}}  the upper classes, being irritated by the inclusionary views and activities of Vaikundar and his popularity, made several attempts to eliminate him and all of them failed.{{sfn|Umai|2003|p=74-76}} So they eventually conspired to kill him in by clandestine means. {{sfn|Umai|2003|p=76-77}}  They pretend to be get convinced to his view and pretend to celebrate him and his preachings. They invited him for a banquet at [[Marunthuvazh Malai]]. He was served with poison through food. To every bodies wonder he remained unaffected. {{sfn|Umai|2003|p=77-82}} But that the poison made some effects on him gradually and that the illness is due to the effects of the poison.{{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=86}} The severity of illness increased as days passed on.{{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=20}} Gradually he was reduced to the bed. He suffered acute pain for more than a year. The whole village was anxious over the suffering of Vaikundar.{{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=20}}\n\nThe days passed and Vaikundar attained the age of 24. Veyilal, the mother informed that{{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=78}} she was instructed by Lord Vishnu that his son will be cured off the illness if he was brought to the festival at Tiruchendur on the 19th of Masi 1008 M.E.{{sfn|Vivekanandan|2003|p=81}} The villagers along with his kith and kin{{sfn|Umai Thanu|2003|p=95}} began the journey carrying Vaikundar in the cradle to [[Tiruchendur]] in the late hours of 15th Masi 1008. M.E.{{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=23}} It is vividly clear that Veyilal, the mother of Vaikundar accompanied him. But very few accounts suggest that Thirumalammal and Ponnu Madan is along with him during his journey.{{sfn|Umai Thanu|2003|p=95}} Authors Krishna Nathan and Kasi Udhayam made claims that the father and wife of Vaikundar were with Vaikundar on his way to Tiruchendur. \nOn the way they took rest alongside a village well after having their meals.{{sfn|Vivekanandan|2003|p=81}} Wondering everybody, Vaikundar, who was until then could not set his foot on the ground, suddenly stepped out of the cradle and started walking swiftly and everybody else followed him.{{sfn|Vivekanandan|2003|p=83}} They believed that the dream of Veyilal is coming true. They reached Tiruchendur on 19th Masi 1008 M.E. and took part in the Masi festival at [[Tiruchendur]].\n\nThe events surrounding the passage of Vaikundar towards the sea is a matter of conflict. On account propound that, during the late night while everybody except Veyilal were sleeping Vaikundar began walking swiftly towards the sea.{{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|pp=43}} Veyilal started to run screaming behind him. The relatives arose and they started running behind Veyilal up to the sea shore and that all of them witness the disappearance of Vaikundar into the sea. {{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|pp=43}} Another narrative is that while they are taking a holy dip in the sea they found Vaikundar missing among the crowd and was not traced.{{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=44}}{{sfn|Ponneelan|2013|p=57}} Other authors opined that he was carried away by a massive wave<ref name=Poulose>{{cite book|last1=Poulose|first1=C|title=Advaita Philosophy of Brahmasri Chattampi Swamikal|date=2002|publisher=Ayya Vaikundanathar Sidhasrama|location=Maruthuvazh Malai|page=23|edition=First}}</ref> on 1 March.{{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=58}} Hours afterwards, with no signs of Vaikundar being found anywhere there, everybody else started convincing Veyilal in one way or another to return home.{{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=29}} Highly distressed Veyilal decided not to go home without her son and remained weeping on the sea-shore.{{sfn|Poulose|2002|p=23}}\n\nAfter three days on 20th Masi 1008. M.E.,{{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|p=44}} the face of Vaikundar was seen rising over the horizon{{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=58}} in the early morning hours. Writer Ponnu suggests that Vaikundar took his rebirth during the auspicious occasion of the Mahamaham,{{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=58}} suggesting the date of the event on 5 March 1833. Few authors suggest that the relatives also witnessed the event{{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|p=44}} while others maintain that all others except Veyilal went disappointed and that she alone was at the sea-shore after three days. The mother was very much excited to see Vaikundar back.{{sfn|Umai|2003|p=113, 114}} However, the words of Vaikundar, after his advent from the sea shocked her as he proclaimed that he is no longer her son. He also revealed that, ''\u201cUntil the year \u2018One thousand and Eight\u2019 you were known to be my mother and now I had born as the son of Narayana for fulfilling the needs of Santror and to rule them forever.\u201d''{{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=58,59}}\n\n==Penance==\n\nAfter making the proclamations, Vaikundar proceeded towards [[Kanyakumari]]. There he instructed the people to give-up the [[rituals]] and religious ceremonies {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=46}} and reached Poovandanthope .{{sfn|Vivekanandan|2003|p=84}} It appears that few incidents in which he was ill-treated happened on the way.{{sfn|Ponnu|2002|pp=62-63}} On the other hand he was also warmly welcomed at some places.{{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=46}} He was also said to have performed [[miracle]]s at various places through the way {{sfn|Amalan|2000|pp=37-41}} As per writer Amalan, Vaikundar stayed at [[Udangudi]] on Masi 21 and reached Poovandanthoppe on 22 Masi 1008 M.E. .{{sfn|Amalan|2000|pp=43-44}} The news about the Thiruchendur incident spread all around the Villages nearby. After this incident people started calling him devoutly as \u2018Ayya\u2019 {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=44}} means Father in [[Tamil language|Tamil]]. He also travelled northwards to various parts of [[Tirunelveli]] to reveal his arrival. He travelled northwards up to [[Kadambankulam]], through Pillaiyar Kudiyiruppu, [[Avaraikulam]], [[Vadakkankulam]], and [[Nizhal Thangal of Pambankulam|Pambankulam]]. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|pp=45-48}} At [[Kadambankulam]], the northernmost venue to which Vaikundar travelled, today stands one among the  rare [[Nizhal Thangal]]s which face geographic north. Vaikundar selected five [[Seedars]]. Two among them, Dharma Seedar and Bheeman Seedar were selected before his northwards travel, Arjunan Seedar was identified during the travel while the remaining two of them, Sahadevan Seedar, and Nakulan Seedar were selected after the travel. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|pp=45-48}}  Though Arjunan Seedar was identified earlier he was selected only afterwards. The episode of his northwards travel was documented  in very few sources.\n\nAfter concluding his travel he returned to [[Swamithope]] by December 1833 {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=51}} and commenced his [[penance]] {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=46}} by mid January 1834 {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=51}} during the auspicious month of [[Margazhi]]. It consists of three phases. The first phase of his penance last for two years from January 1843 to December 1835. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=53}} The ''Phase I'' is named [[Yuga]] Thavasu and was intended to abolish the rule of the evil force, Kali and for the subsequent end of Kali Yuga. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=79}} The Yuga Thavasu is performed in a standing posture {{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|p=45}} within a 6 feet-deep pit. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=79}} During this phase he use to talk less and believed to have taken no food. {{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|p=45}} The second Phase is dedicated for the elimination of the case based and other discriminations among human communities and for the upliftment of [[The Santror|Santror]]. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=79}} The second phase too lasted for two years beginning on December 1835 till December 1837. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=54}} This phase is performed at the ground level in a sitting posture. {{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|p=45}} He took only [[rice gruel]] .{{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|pp=45-46}} However, some sources claimed that he took milk and fruits during ''Phase II'' .{{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=46}}\n\n''Phase III'' of the penance began by January 1838. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=54}}  This last phase is meant for the upliftment of women and for the betterment of his [[offspring|progeny]]. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=79}} Phase III is performed by him on a raised pedestal. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=79}} The last phase too was intended to extend for two complete years but was interrupted by the [[Swathi Thirunal Rama Varma|King of Travancore]]. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=54}}\n\n== Mendicant==\n\nBy this time it is believed that so many miracles began to happen around him and people started believing his as their saviour.{{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|p=45}}  The news began to spread like wild-fire and thousands of people from every section of the society {{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|p=46}} from the surrounding villages began to visit Swamithope, believing that their grievances be addressed by him. {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=46}} He is believed to have cured various diseases during this period. {{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|p=46}} People witnessed mysterious experience and influence while standing before him {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=46}} Some accounts suggests that attempts were made by the upper classes during this time to dispel his popularity. {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=47}} During this time he also believed to have incinerated the [[demon]]s and also seized the power of the [[witchcraft]], [[Magic (paranormal)|sorcery]] etc in front of his devotees.{{sfn|Patrick|2003|pp=80-81}}\n\nVaikundar characterised himself as a [[Mendicant]]. He was addressed by the worshippers as ''\u2018Narayana Pandaram\u2019''.{{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=81}}  It was during these days he preached several revolutionary ideas which are considered as historically unparalleled. He emphasized the importance of [[Charity (practice)|Charity]], [[Truth]] and [[love]] and induced these values into the [[ritual]]s.{{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=47}}  Most of his teachings and rituals he advocated has both religious and social implications. Historically, the rituals were used or viewed as an attempt to break the inequalities, mainly caste-based, prevailed in the society of the time, and to strengthen and uplift the sociologically downtrodden and ill-treated. Examples of this include the charity on food as 'Anna Dharmam' , physical as well as spiritual cleanliness through [[Thuvayal Thavasu]],<ref name=\"Mythic society\">{{cite journal|last1=Society|first1=Mythic|title=The Quarterly Journal of the Mythic Society|date=1986|volume=77|page=258|url=https://books.google.com/?id=zBa2AAAAIAAJ&dq=Sami+thope&q=Sami+thope|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> eliminating untouchability through [[Thirunamam|Thottunamam]], self-respect and courage through headgear,{{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|pp=93-96}} and unifying various castes through [[Muthirikkinaru]]. His revolutionary doctrine caused great excitement among the people and prepared them to fight for their rights. (SFSE 48)   During this time he also believed to have incinerated the demons and also seized the power of the [[witchcraft]], [[Magic (paranormal)|sorcery]] etc. in front of his devotees. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|pp=80-81}}\n\n== Arrest ==\n\nThe teachings of Vaikundar created an excitement among the people and it began to reflect in the socio-religious arena of the 19th century South Travancore and South [[Tirunelveli]]. The lower classes began to resist several oppressions all of them until then remained unchallenged. The upper classes viewed this as a challenge against them as they believed that the collapse of the existing system may undermine their social status seriously. Numerous complaints were made before the King of Travancore by the upper classes against Vaikundar and his activities. {{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=68}} But the king seems to ignore all of them initially. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=82}} The issue was brought before the king [[Swathi Thirunal Rama Varma]] once again during his [[Suchindrum]] visit. {{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=69}} Being a staunch believer of the Varna system, it seems hard for the King to believe Vaikundar, whose community was outside the caste-fold, to be the [[avatar]] of [[Narayana]]. {{sfn|Vivekanandan|2003|p=90}} Moreover, the claim made by Vaikundar that himself will rule the world as an undisputed King misled the king. He suspected that Vaikundar was provoking the people and was plotting for a revolt against the Kingdom. {{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=70}} Fearing a revolution he sent the armed forces immediately to arrest Vaikundar {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=50}} <ref>{{cite book|last1=Kasturi|first1=Prema|last2=Madhavan|first2=Chithra|title=South India heritage: An introduction|date=2007|publisher=East West Books (Madras)|isbn=9788188661640|page=107}}</ref>  The large gathering around Vaikundar confronted with the army. Vaikundar refrained them from getting violent {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=50}} and appealed them to pave the way for the forces. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=58-59}} The soldiers arrested him and took him to Suchindrum. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=82}}\n\nAt Suchindrum, Vaikundar was brought in front of the king. He, who already had doubts about the [[divinity]] of Vaikundar, intended to test his [[supernatural]] ability {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=82}} by hiding his ring in his hand and asking him to name it. {{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=76}} Vaikundar preferred not to answer and to remain silent {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=82}} The king ordered his imprisonment immediately {{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|p=51}} He was imprisoned in a confinement filled with sewage infested with worms {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=82}} It is also noted by some that he was asked to take alcohol in which various poisonous herbs  was mixed up. Miraculously Vaikundar remained unaffected {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=61}} He was imprisoned there for two days. Then the king ordered him to be taken to [[Thiruvananthapuram]], the capital of [[Travancore]]. The forces proceed towards Thiruvananthapuram through [[Kottar]], [[Parvathipuram, Tamil Nadu|Parvathipuram]], [[Chungankadai]] and reached [[Thuckalay]]. That night he was kept imprisoned at [[Manalikkara]] .{{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=61}} The next day the soldiers took him to Thiruvananthapuram via [[Balaramapuram]]. At Thiruvananthapuram, Vaikundar was jailed at Singarathope open prison. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=61}} Jubliant followers of Vaikundar accompanied him all through his way and stayed at the prison premises {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=62}}\n\nDuring his imprisonment period people in large numbers rushed to Singarathope to avail his blessings. {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=50}} Vaikundar was subjected to several severe tribulations and cruel treatments. However, he continued preaching and healing there too. {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=50}} He also said to have performed various miracles at the prison {{sfn|Amalan|2000|pp=70-71}} Attempts were also made to burn him in lime [[kiln]] and in Chilli go-down. He had overcome all these miraculously. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=67-73}} He was finally thrown into the cage of a hungry [[Tiger]] in front of the administrators, army staff and public. Contrary to the expectation of the officials the tiger did not jump onto its prey. One of the soldiers tried to prod it with a spear in order to provoke it. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=83}} The tiger caught hold of the spear and in no time left it abruptly when the other end of the spear ripped the abdomen of a priest and he died on the spot. This event shocked the king as he believed that killing a priest would fetch divine wrath.{{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=83}} He ordered the release of Vaikundar immediately upon the condition that he would restrict his activities and preaching only to his caste. Vaikundar not only refused to sign the condition but also refused to accept his release. He tore the royal writ into pieces since his mission was the betterment and equality of all castes.{{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=51}} He proclaimed that he would be accepting the release only after the completion imprisonment period.\n\nHe remained in jail as a prisoner for the full 3&thinsp;\u00be months. He was released after 110 days, in the first week of March. These events enhanced the fame of Vaikundar further all over the kingdom. {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=51}} His followers carried him back as a procession and they reached Poovandanthope on 19 Masi 1013 [[Malayalam Era|M.E]] (1 March 1838), a day before the 5th anniversary of his incarnation.\n\n==Later life==\n\nAs the Phase III of his [[Tavam of Vaikundar|Tavam]] was disrupted by the King he decided to fulfil the penance. He also directed 700 families to undertake [[Thuvayal Thavasu]], the Washing Penance. They concluded the penance at two Phases. Phase I last for 6 months and was conducted at [[Vakaippathi]] and Phase II lasts another 6 months at Muttapathi. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=79-86}} By the same time the final phase of Tavam of Vaikundar too completed at Poovandanthope. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=86}} After the conclusion of the Tavam he consecrated the [[Muthirikkinaru]], historically the first ever well in South India which was allowed to be used by all castes. He was also believed to be received the Second [[Vinchai]] from Lord Narayana at ''Theerthakkarai'', [[Muttapathi]]. Then he moved westwards to the place which was now known to be as Ambala Pathi.{{fact|date=April 2018}}\n\nAt [[Ambalappathi]], he portrayed himself as a reigning King under a grand roof similar to the ones in the then Travancore palace. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=83}} He was also believed to have unified various deighties into himself there by conducting a grand ceremony, Ikanai manam. .{{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|p=56}} Afterwards he also laid foundation stones for several [[Nizhal Thangal]]s throughout South Travancore and South Tirunelvely. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=84}} He breathed his last in 21 [[Tamil calendar|Vaikasi]] 1026.[[Malayalam Era|M.E]] His '' \u2018Sacred Golden Body\u2019 '' was interned at Poovandanthope which was now the [[Palliyarai]] of [[Swamithope Pathi]].{{fact|date=April 2018}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book |last=Vivekanandan |first=Siva |date=December 2003 |title=Ayya Vaikundar : Vazhvum Vazhibadum |publisher=Kavya |edition=1st |language=Tamil |trans-title=Ayya Vaikundar : Life and Worship }}\n* G. Patrick (2003), ''Religion and Subaltern Agency'', Department of Christian Studies, [[University of Madras]], [[Chennai]].\n* T. Krishnanathan (2000), ''Ayya Vaikundarin Vazhvum Sinthanaiyum'', [[Madurai Kamaraj University]], Thinai Publications, [[Nagercoil]].\n* C. Paulose (2002), ''Advaita Philosophy of Brahmasri Chattampi Swamikal'', Sree Sankaracharya University of Sanskrit, Ayya Vaikunta Nather Sidhasramam, Pothaiyadi.\n* R. Ponnu (2000), ''Sri Vaikunda Swamigal and Struggle for Social Equality in South India'', [[Madurai Kamaraj University]], Ram Publishers, [[Madurai]].\n* R. Ponnu (2002), ''Vaikunda Swamikal Ore Avataram'', Ram Publishers, Madurai.\n* R. Shunmugam (2001), ''Nadar Kulathil Narayanar Avataram'', Nadar Kuladeepam Publications, Karankadu.\n* Samuel Mateer (1871), ''The Land of charity: a descriptive account of Travancore and its people, Asian Educational Services'', {{ISBN|81-206-0319-2}}\n* V.T. Chellam (2002), ''Thamizaka Varalarum Panpadum'' (The History and Culture of Tamil Nadu), Manickavasakar Publications, Chennai.\n* [[Madanjeet Singh]] (2005), ''The Sasia Story'', France, {{ISBN|92-3-103992-X}}.\n* P. Sundaram Swamigal and K. Ponnumani (2001), ''Ayyavaikundanathar Jeevacharithram'' (Biography of Ayya Vaikunta Nathar), Ayyavaikuntanathar Siddasramam Publications, Pothaiyadi.\n* V. Nagam Aiya (1989), ''The Travancore State Manual'', Volume-2, [[Asian Educational Services]], {{ISBN|81-85499-33-0}}.\n* P. Sarvesvaran, ''Sri Vaikunda Swamikal \u2013 A Forgotten Social Reformer''.\n* N. Amalan (2000), ''Ayya Vaikundar Punitha Varalaru'', Akilam Publications, Swamithoppu.\n* Samuel Zecharia (1897), ''The London Missionary Society in South Travancore 1805\u20131855'', [[London Missionary Society|LMS]] Press, Nagercoil.\n* M. S. S. Pandiyan (1992)  ''Meanings of 'colonialism' and 'nationalism''': an essay on Vaikunda Swamy cult, Sage Publications\n* A. Sreedhara Menon (1967), ''A Survey of Kerala History'', D.C. Books, Kottayam, {{ISBN|81-264-1578-9}}\n* Dr. M. Immanuel (2007), ''Kanniyakumari: Aspects and Architects'', Historical Research & Publications Trust, Nagercoil, {{ISBN|978-81-901506-2-0}}\n\n==Citations==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Ayya Vaikundar]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Vaikundar---Historical-vs-Religious.png|thumb|200px|[[Vaikundar]] : Historical vs Spiritual views]]\n'''Historical Vaikundar''' (1809\u20131851) refers to the life and teachings of [[Ayya Vaikundar]], as known in [[Akilathirattu Ammanai]], being reconstructed from a historical perspective with reference to various historical sources in contrast to the mythological [[Akilam]]ic views. Though few events referred to in the mythology have yet to be validated historically, many key events mentioned in [[Akilam]] were acknowledged  by  other contemporary  sources.\n\nAyya Vaikundar was the first<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.hindu.com/2004/08/29/stories/2004082904420400.htm|title= The Hindu |accessdate=7 February 2007 |format= The Sree Narayana effect|work=Credit to reformers: \"The first of the social revolutionaries was Vaikunta Swami (1809\u20131851).\" |location=Chennai, India |date=29 August 2004| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070305164930/http://www.hindu.com/2004/08/29/stories/2004082904420400.htm| archivedate= 5 March 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> to succeed as a social reformer<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.hindu.com/2006/03/19/stories/2006031900640200.htm|title= The Hindu|accessdate=7 February 2007 |format= `Communalism an important factor in politics'|work=Great reformers|location=Chennai, India|date=19 March 2006| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070111132234/http://www.hindu.com/2006/03/19/stories/2006031900640200.htm| archivedate= 11 January 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.hindu.com/2004/07/06/stories/2004070612160300.htm|title= The Hindu \u2013 India's National Newspaper|accessdate=16 September 2007 |format= Around the City|work=AIR programme|location=Chennai, India|date=6 July 2004}} This link about a programme by '[[All India Radio]]' includes [[Ayya Vaikundar]] as a [[Social reformer]].</ref> in launching political struggle,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.hindu.com/cp/2007/09/28/stories/2007092850300800.htm|title= The Hindu \u2013 India's National Newspaper|accessdate=23 January 2008 |format= Stargazing|work=Ayya's story|location=Chennai, India|date=28 September 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080214111454/http://www.hindu.com/cp/2007/09/28/stories/2007092850300800.htm| archivedate= 14 February 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> social renaissance<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.education.kerala.gov.in/englishmedium/historyeng/chapter9.pdf|title= www.education.kerala.gov.in|accessdate= 23 January 2008|format= Towards Modern Kerala|work= 10th Standard Text Book, Chapter 9, p. 101.|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081217193847/http://www.education.kerala.gov.in/englishmedium/historyeng/chapter9.pdf|archivedate= 17 December 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dinamalar.com/2008MAR03/general_tn7.asp |title=www.dinamalar.com |accessdate=3 May 2008 |format=Silently spreading Love-flag |work=Dinamalar (Leading Tamil Daily), 3 March 2008. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202150511/http://dinamalar.com/2008MAR03/general_tn7.asp |archivedate=2 December 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tnuniv.ac.in/tansche/reports/History%20Education%20in%20the%2021st%20Century.pdf |title=www.tnuniv.ac.in |accessdate=16 September 2007 |format=Tamil Nadu State Council for Higher Education, Social and Cultural History of Tamil Nadu from 1529 to Present day |work=Reform Movements and National Movement, p. 27 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071129185218/http://www.tnuniv.ac.in/tansche/reports/History%20Education%20in%20the%2021st%20Century.pdf |archivedate=29 November 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> as well as religious reformation<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdu.ac.in/cb-ug-his.pdf |title=History of Tamil Nadu from 1800 AD to the Present Day |accessdate=23 January 2008 |format=Bharathidasan University |work=B.A. History \u2013 Course Structure under CBCS, Core Course \u2013 V, p. 9. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071129185219/http://www.bdu.ac.in/cb-ug-his.pdf |archivedate=29 November 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdu.ac.in/cb-pg-his.pdf |title=www.bdu.ac.in |accessdate=7 February 2007 |format=SOCIAL REFORMERS OF MODERN INDIA |work=Unit IV |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051128094048/http://www.bdu.ac.in/cb-pg-his.pdf |archivedate=28 November 2005 }}</ref> Vaikundar was the pioneer of the social revolutionaries of south India<ref>M. Ilanchezhiyan, ''Pandiyarkula Nadrakal Kulamurai Kilathal'', p. 197.</ref> and Kerala.<ref name = \"Sreedharamenon\"/> Research scholars regard Vaikundar as a teacher, healer and also a miracle worker.<ref>George D. Chryssides, ''Historical dictionary of new religious movements'', (Publisher: Lanham, Md., Scarecrow Press) 2012, Page 48, Ayyavazhi.</ref> He was also said to be the forerunner of all social reformers of India.<ref name= \"Immanuel:First Reform Movement\">Immanuel, ''Kanniyakumari: Aspects and Architects'', Chapter 11, pp. 115\u2013116.</ref>  He was in the forefront of movements for Human Rights and Social Equality.<ref name= \"Immanuel:First Reform Movement\" /> His teachings also effected many social changes in southern India,<ref>R. Ponnu, ''Vaikunda Swamigal Ore Avataram'', p. 152</ref> resulting in the emergence of a series of social and [[self-respect movement]]s such as ''Upper cloth agitation'',<ref name = \"Sreedharamenon\">A. Sreedhara Menon, ''A Survey of Kerala History'', p. 314</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/article1064574.ece|title= The Hindu|accessdate=3 March 2011 |format= Jayalalithaa to visit Kanyakumari tomorrow|work=' \"He (Vaikundar) spearheaded the thol seelai struggle...\" ' 3 March 2011.}}</ref> [[Temple Entry Proclamation|Temple entry agitation]] and other movements including those of [[Narayana Guru]],<ref name= \"Selvister:First Reform Movement\" >Selvister Ponnumuthan, (1996), ''The spirituality of basic ecclesial communities in the socio-religious context of Trivandrum/Kerala, India'', {{ISBN|88-7652-721-4}}, Editrice Pontificia Universit\u00e0 Gregoriana, pp. 77\u201378</ref> [[Chattampi Swamikal]], [[Arutprakasa Vallalar Chidambaram Ramalinga Swamigal|Vallalar]]<ref name= \"Ponnu:First Reform Movement\" >R. Ponnu, ''Vaikunda swamigal Ore Avataram'', p. 178.</ref> and [[Ayyankali]].\n\n==Early life==\n\nThe year as well as the exact date of birth of Vaikundar is a matter of conflict.  Various historians place the year of birth as 1809 C.E while as few other sources placed his birth in 1808 C.E. Akilam did not mention any direct reference to the date. But by the time he was taken to [[Tiruchendur]] for being cured after he fall sick he was at his 24, for which the exact date is mentioned in Akilam as 20th Masi 1008 M.E which falls on 4 March 1833. The date of birth too is subject to greater conflict. Historians predict various dates from 12 March to 19 April. He has born as the second son to ''Ponnumadan - Veyilal couple''.\n\nThe parents<ref name=vsoa>{{cite book|last1=Ponnu|first1=Ira|title=Vaikunda Swamigal Ore Avatarm|date=2002|publisher=Ram Publishers|location=Madurai|page=52|edition=First}}</ref> and the villagers<ref name=avpv>{{cite book|last1=Amalan|first1=N|title=Ayya Vaikundar Punitha Varalaru|date=2001|publisher=Akilam Publishers|location=Swamithope|page=40|edition=First}}</ref> witnessed some spiritual significance<ref name=Ponnu>{{cite book|last1=Ponnu|first1=R|title=Sri Vaikunda Swamigal and The Struggle for Social Equality in South India|date=2000|publisher=Ram Publishers|location=Madurai|pages=40\u201341|edition=First}}</ref> in the face of the child. A naming ceremony was conducted and the name ''Mudisoodum Perumal (Lord Vishnu with Crown)'' was suggested by the elders and was accepted by others. Since people of lower castes are not allowed to use the names of God or [[Travancore royal family|Rulers]] the upper classes opposed the move<ref name=rasa>{{cite book|last1=Patrick|first1=G|title=Religion and Subaltern Agency|date=2003|publisher=University of Madras|location=Chennai|page=77}}</ref> and demanded an immediate name change.{{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=41}}Fearing the oppression the child was renamed ''Muthukutty''. There are various accounts as to who suggested the name. While few historians claim that the name Muthukutty, which tones prosaical, was suggested by the officials, others argued that though some officials from the administration were against the name '' \u2018Mudisoodum Perumal\u2019 '', they never suggested this alternative. There is another account that while the parents was seeking admission to the child for schooling in a traditional Schools known as ''Thinnai Palli'' the teacher refused to enrol the child with the name and he himself changed the name to Muthukutty.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Vivekanandan|first1=Siva|title=Ayya Vaikundar Vazhvum Vazhibadum|date=2003|publisher=Kavya|location=Chennai|page=78|edition=First}}</ref> Another narration is that the [[Kingdom of Travancore|King of Travancore]], through his Umbrella bearer, Poovandar, directly ordered to change the name which includes the suffix \u2018Perumal\u2019 (Vishnu) to Muthukutty. {{sfn|Amalan|2001|p=8}} Other accounts speculates that the villagers themselves adopted the name as per the existing norms<ref name=\"rasa\" /> as the lower castes of the [[Travancore]] has to use differential language and different set of names to signify their differential social status from the upper classes.{{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=85}}\n\nThough he disliked [[rituals]] and practices {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=42}} he was very religious {{sfn|Amalan|2001|p=6}} and prefers simple worship. {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=42}} He was also very revolutionary in his thoughts, idea and acts right from his childhood. {{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=55}} He was a staunch devotee of Lord Vishnu as he had set a pedestal{{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=55}} and offers regular prayers for [[Vishnu]] at his residence. He  use to meditate regularly during evenings at [[Marunthuvazh Malai]].{{sfn|Amalan|2001|p=6}} He well versed in various ancient arts including [[martial art]]s, {{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=55}} he appears as a multifaceted personality. {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=42}} He was also said to be a very good orator. {{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=55}} Though it is not clear whether he advocated a unified society and supported intermingling of various castes and promoted inter-caste marriages. But he strongly propagated for a society totally free from caste discrimination and also worked for the betterment of the downtrodden. {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=42}} He was intensely against the oppressive treatment of the lower classes. {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=43}}\n\n==Transformation==\n\nAt the age of 17 he married <ref name=Malar>{{cite book|last1=Umai Thanu|first1=C|last2=Kasi Udhayam|first2=P|title=Bhagavan Vaikunda Swamigal Punitha Varalaru|date=2003|publisher=Dinamalar|location=Chennai|pages=65, 66|edition=Second}}</ref> a women Thirumalammal of Puviyoor, Agastheeswaram,{{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=42}} who was left alone by her husband. There is also a view that they never get married and that the women only came to serve him in his activities .{{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=86}} He continued his early life as a [[Palmyra]] Climber <ref name=Mateer>{{cite book|last1=Mateer|first1=Samuel|title=The Land of charity: a descriptive account of Travancore and its people|date=1871|publisher=Asian Educational Services|location=New Delhi|isbn=81-206-0319-2|page=222}}</ref> and as an Agricultural labourer. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=78}} At the age of 22 he fall ill.\n\nThere is another narrative that at his age of 16,{{sfn|Amalan|2000|pp=15}}  the upper classes, being irritated by the inclusionary views and activities of Vaikundar and his popularity, made several attempts to eliminate him and all of them failed.{{sfn|Umai|2003|p=74-76}} So they eventually conspired to kill him in by clandestine means. {{sfn|Umai|2003|p=76-77}}  They pretend to be get convinced to his view and pretend to celebrate him and his preachings. They invited him for a banquet at [[Marunthuvazh Malai]]. He was served with poison through food. To every bodies wonder he remained unaffected. {{sfn|Umai|2003|p=77-82}} But that the poison made some effects on him gradually and that the illness is due to the effects of the poison.{{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=86}} The severity of illness increased as days passed on.{{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=20}} Gradually he was reduced to the bed. He suffered acute pain for more than a year. The whole village was anxious over the suffering of Vaikundar.{{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=20}}\n\nThe days passed and Vaikundar attained the age of 24. Veyilal, the mother informed that{{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=78}} she was instructed by Lord Vishnu that his son will be cured off the illness if he was brought to the festival at Tiruchendur on the 19th of Masi 1008 M.E.{{sfn|Vivekanandan|2003|p=81}} The villagers along with his kith and kin{{sfn|Umai Thanu|2003|p=95}} began the journey carrying Vaikundar in the cradle to [[Tiruchendur]] in the late hours of 15th Masi 1008. M.E.{{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=23}} It is vividly clear that Veyilal, the mother of Vaikundar accompanied him. But very few accounts suggest that Thirumalammal and Ponnu Madan is along with him during his journey.{{sfn|Umai Thanu|2003|p=95}} Authors Krishna Nathan and Kasi Udhayam made claims that the father and wife of Vaikundar were with Vaikundar on his way to Tiruchendur. \nOn the way they took rest alongside a village well after having their meals.{{sfn|Vivekanandan|2003|p=81}} Wondering everybody, Vaikundar, who was until then could not set his foot on the ground, suddenly stepped out of the cradle and started walking swiftly and everybody else followed him.{{sfn|Vivekanandan|2003|p=83}} They believed that the dream of Veyilal is coming true. They reached Tiruchendur on 19th Masi 1008 M.E. and took part in the Masi festival at [[Tiruchendur]].\n\nThe events surrounding the passage of Vaikundar towards the sea is a matter of conflict. On account propound that, during the late night while everybody except Veyilal were sleeping Vaikundar began walking swiftly towards the sea.{{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|pp=43}} Veyilal started to run screaming behind him. The relatives arose and they started running behind Veyilal up to the sea shore and that all of them witness the disappearance of Vaikundar into the sea. {{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|pp=43}} Another narrative is that while they are taking a holy dip in the sea they found Vaikundar missing among the crowd and was not traced.{{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=44}}{{sfn|Ponneelan|2013|p=57}} Other authors opined that he was carried away by a massive wave<ref name=Poulose>{{cite book|last1=Poulose|first1=C|title=Advaita Philosophy of Brahmasri Chattampi Swamikal|date=2002|publisher=Ayya Vaikundanathar Sidhasrama|location=Maruthuvazh Malai|page=23|edition=First}}</ref> on 1 March.{{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=58}} Hours afterwards, with no signs of Vaikundar being found anywhere there, everybody else started convincing Veyilal in one way or another to return home.{{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=29}} Highly distressed Veyilal decided not to go home without her son and remained weeping on the sea-shore.{{sfn|Poulose|2002|p=23}}\n\nAfter three days on 20th Masi 1008. M.E.,{{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|p=44}} the face of Vaikundar was seen rising over the horizon{{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=58}} in the early morning hours. Writer Ponnu suggests that Vaikundar took his rebirth during the auspicious occasion of the Mahamaham,{{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=58}} suggesting the date of the event on 5 March 1833. Few authors suggest that the relatives also witnessed the event{{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|p=44}} while others maintain that all others except Veyilal went disappointed and that she alone was at the sea-shore after three days. The mother was very much excited to see Vaikundar back.{{sfn|Umai|2003|p=113, 114}} However, the words of Vaikundar, after his advent from the sea shocked her as he proclaimed that he is no longer her son. He also revealed that, ''\u201cUntil the year \u2018One thousand and Eight\u2019 you were known to be my mother and now I had born as the son of Narayana for fulfilling the needs of Santror and to rule them forever.\u201d''{{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=58,59}}\n\n==Penance==\n\nAfter making the proclamations, Vaikundar proceeded towards [[Kanyakumari]]. There he instructed the people to give-up the [[rituals]] and religious ceremonies {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=46}} and reached Poovandanthope .{{sfn|Vivekanandan|2003|p=84}} It appears that few incidents in which he was ill-treated happened on the way.{{sfn|Ponnu|2002|pp=62-63}} On the other hand he was also warmly welcomed at some places.{{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=46}} He was also said to have performed [[miracle]]s at various places through the way {{sfn|Amalan|2000|pp=37-41}} As per writer Amalan, Vaikundar stayed at [[Udangudi]] on Masi 21 and reached Poovandanthoppe on 22 Masi 1008 M.E. .{{sfn|Amalan|2000|pp=43-44}} The news about the Thiruchendur incident spread all around the Villages nearby. After this incident people started calling him devoutly as \u2018Ayya\u2019 {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=44}} means Father in [[Tamil language|Tamil]]. He also travelled northwards to various parts of [[Tirunelveli]] to reveal his arrival. He travelled northwards up to [[Kadambankulam]], through Pillaiyar Kudiyiruppu, [[Avaraikulam]], [[Vadakkankulam]], and [[Nizhal Thangal of Pambankulam|Pambankulam]]. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|pp=45-48}} At [[Kadambankulam]], the northernmost venue to which Vaikundar travelled, today stands one among the  rare [[Nizhal Thangal]]s which face geographic north. Vaikundar selected five [[Seedars]]. Two among them, Dharma Seedar and Bheeman Seedar were selected before his northwards travel, Arjunan Seedar was identified during the travel while the remaining two of them, Sahadevan Seedar, and Nakulan Seedar were selected after the travel. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|pp=45-48}}  Though Arjunan Seedar was identified earlier he was selected only afterwards. The episode of his northwards travel was documented  in very few sources.\n\nAfter concluding his travel he returned to [[Swamithope]] by December 1833 {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=51}} and commenced his [[penance]] {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=46}} by mid January 1834 {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=51}} during the auspicious month of [[Margazhi]]. It consists of three phases. The first phase of his penance last for two years from January 1843 to December 1835. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=53}} The ''Phase I'' is named [[Yuga]] Thavasu and was intended to abolish the rule of the evil force, Kali and for the subsequent end of Kali Yuga. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=79}} The Yuga Thavasu is performed in a standing posture {{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|p=45}} within a 6 feet-deep pit. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=79}} During this phase he use to talk less and believed to have taken no food. {{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|p=45}} The second Phase is dedicated for the elimination of the case based and other discriminations among human communities and for the upliftment of [[The Santror|Santror]]. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=79}} The second phase too lasted for two years beginning on December 1835 till December 1837. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=54}} This phase is performed at the ground level in a sitting posture. {{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|p=45}} He took only [[rice gruel]] .{{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|pp=45-46}} However, some sources claimed that he took milk and fruits during ''Phase II'' .{{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=46}}\n\n''Phase III'' of the penance began by January 1838. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=54}}  This last phase is meant for the upliftment of women and for the betterment of his [[offspring|progeny]]. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=79}} Phase III is performed by him on a raised pedestal. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=79}} The last phase too was intended to extend for two complete years but was interrupted by the [[Swathi Thirunal Rama Varma|King of Travancore]]. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=54}}\n\n== Mendicant==\n\nBy this time it is believed that so many miracles began to happen around him and people started believing his as their saviour.{{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|p=45}}  The news began to spread like wild-fire and thousands of people from every section of the society {{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|p=46}} from the surrounding villages began to visit Swamithope, believing that their grievances be addressed by him. {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=46}} He is believed to have cured various diseases during this period. {{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|p=46}} People witnessed mysterious experience and influence while standing before him {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=46}} Some accounts suggests that attempts were made by the upper classes during this time to dispel his popularity. {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=47}} During this time he also believed to have incinerated the [[demon]]s and also seized the power of the [[witchcraft]], [[Magic (paranormal)|sorcery]] etc in front of his devotees.{{sfn|Patrick|2003|pp=80-81}}\n\nVaikundar characterised himself as a [[Mendicant]]. He was addressed by the worshippers as ''\u2018Narayana Pandaram\u2019''.{{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=81}}  It was during these days he preached several revolutionary ideas which are considered as historically unparalleled. He emphasized the importance of [[Charity (practice)|Charity]], [[Truth]] and [[love]] and induced these values into the [[ritual]]s.{{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=47}}  Most of his teachings and rituals he advocated has both religious and social implications. Historically, the rituals were used or viewed as an attempt to break the inequalities, mainly caste-based, prevailed in the society of the time, and to strengthen and uplift the sociologically downtrodden and ill-treated. Examples of this include the charity on food as 'Anna Dharmam' , physical as well as spiritual cleanliness through [[Thuvayal Thavasu]],<ref name=\"Mythic society\">{{cite journal|last1=Society|first1=Mythic|title=The Quarterly Journal of the Mythic Society|date=1986|volume=77|page=258|url=https://books.google.com/?id=zBa2AAAAIAAJ&dq=Sami+thope&q=Sami+thope|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> eliminating untouchability through [[Thirunamam|Thottunamam]], self-respect and courage through headgear,{{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|pp=93-96}} and unifying various castes through [[Muthirikkinaru]]. His revolutionary doctrine caused great excitement among the people and prepared them to fight for their rights. (SFSE 48)   During this time he also believed to have incinerated the demons and also seized the power of the [[witchcraft]], [[Magic (paranormal)|sorcery]] etc. in front of his devotees. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|pp=80-81}}\n\n== Arrest ==\n\nThe teachings of Vaikundar created an excitement among the people and it began to reflect in the socio-religious arena of the 19th century South Travancore and South [[Tirunelveli]]. The lower classes began to resist several oppressions all of them until then remained unchallenged. The upper classes viewed this as a challenge against them as they believed that the collapse of the existing system may undermine their social status seriously. Numerous complaints were made before the King of Travancore by the upper classes against Vaikundar and his activities. {{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=68}} But the king seems to ignore all of them initially. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=82}} The issue was brought before the king [[Swathi Thirunal Rama Varma]] once again during his [[Suchindrum]] visit. {{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=69}} Being a staunch believer of the Varna system, it seems hard for the King to believe Vaikundar, whose community was outside the caste-fold, to be the [[avatar]] of [[Narayana]]. {{sfn|Vivekanandan|2003|p=90}} Moreover, the claim made by Vaikundar that himself will rule the world as an undisputed King misled the king. He suspected that Vaikundar was provoking the people and was plotting for a revolt against the Kingdom. {{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=70}} Fearing a revolution he sent the armed forces immediately to arrest Vaikundar {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=50}} <ref>{{cite book|last1=Kasturi|first1=Prema|last2=Madhavan|first2=Chithra|title=South India heritage: An introduction|date=2007|publisher=East West Books (Madras)|isbn=9788188661640|page=107}}</ref>  The large gathering around Vaikundar confronted with the army. Vaikundar refrained them from getting violent {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=50}} and appealed them to pave the way for the forces. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=58-59}} The soldiers arrested him and took him to Suchindrum. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=82}}\n\nAt Suchindrum, Vaikundar was brought in front of the king. He, who already had doubts about the [[divinity]] of Vaikundar, intended to test his [[supernatural]] ability {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=82}} by hiding his ring in his hand and asking him to name it. {{sfn|Ponnu|2002|p=76}} Vaikundar preferred not to answer and to remain silent {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=82}} The king ordered his imprisonment immediately {{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|p=51}} He was imprisoned in a confinement filled with sewage infested with worms {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=82}} It is also noted by some that he was asked to take alcohol in which various poisonous herbs  was mixed up. Miraculously Vaikundar remained unaffected {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=61}} He was imprisoned there for two days. Then the king ordered him to be taken to [[Thiruvananthapuram]], the capital of [[Travancore]]. The forces proceed towards Thiruvananthapuram through [[Kottar]], [[Parvathipuram, Tamil Nadu|Parvathipuram]], [[Chungankadai]] and reached [[Thuckalay]]. That night he was kept imprisoned at [[Manalikkara]] .{{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=61}} The next day the soldiers took him to Thiruvananthapuram via [[Balaramapuram]]. At Thiruvananthapuram, Vaikundar was jailed at Singarathope open prison. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=61}} Jubliant followers of Vaikundar accompanied him all through his way and stayed at the prison premises {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=62}}\n\nDuring his imprisonment period people in large numbers rushed to Singarathope to avail his blessings. {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=50}} Vaikundar was subjected to several severe tribulations and cruel treatments. However, he continued preaching and healing there too. {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=50}} He also said to have performed various miracles at the prison {{sfn|Amalan|2000|pp=70-71}} Attempts were also made to burn him in lime [[kiln]] and in Chilli go-down. He had overcome all these miraculously. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=67-73}} He was finally thrown into the cage of a hungry [[Tiger]] in front of the administrators, army staff and public. Contrary to the expectation of the officials the tiger did not jump onto its prey. One of the soldiers tried to prod it with a spear in order to provoke it. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=83}} The tiger caught hold of the spear and in no time left it abruptly when the other end of the spear ripped the abdomen of a priest and he died on the spot. This event shocked the king as he believed that killing a priest would fetch divine wrath.{{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=83}} He ordered the release of Vaikundar immediately upon the condition that he would restrict his activities and preaching only to his caste. Vaikundar not only refused to sign the condition but also refused to accept his release. He tore the royal writ into pieces since his mission was the betterment and equality of all castes.{{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=51}} He proclaimed that he would be accepting the release only after the completion imprisonment period.\n\nHe remained in jail as a prisoner for the full 3&thinsp;\u00be months. He was released after 110 days, in the first week of March. These events enhanced the fame of Vaikundar further all over the kingdom. {{sfn|Ponnu|2000|p=51}} His followers carried him back as a procession and they reached Poovandanthope on 19 Masi 1013 [[Malayalam Era|M.E]] (1 March 1838), a day before the 5th anniversary of his incarnation.\n\n==Later life==\n\nAs the Phase III of his [[Tavam of Vaikundar|Tavam]] was disrupted by the King he decided to fulfil the penance. He also directed 700 families to undertake [[Thuvayal Thavasu]], the Washing Penance. They concluded the penance at two Phases. Phase I last for 6 months and was conducted at [[Vakaippathi]] and Phase II lasts another 6 months at Muttapathi. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=79-86}} By the same time the final phase of Tavam of Vaikundar too completed at Poovandanthope. {{sfn|Amalan|2000|p=86}} After the conclusion of the Tavam he consecrated the [[Muthirikkinaru]], historically the first ever well in South India which was allowed to be used by all castes. He was also believed to be received the Second [[Vinchai]] from Lord Narayana at ''Theerthakkarai'', [[Muttapathi]]. Then he moved westwards to the place which was now known to be as Ambala Pathi.{{fact|date=April 2018}}\n\nAt [[Ambalappathi]], he portrayed himself as a reigning King under a grand roof similar to the ones in the then Travancore palace. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=83}} He was also believed to have unified various deighties into himself there by conducting a grand ceremony, Ikanai manam. .{{sfn|Krishnanathan|2000|p=56}} Afterwards he also laid foundation stones for several [[Nizhal Thangal]]s throughout South Travancore and South Tirunelvely. {{sfn|Patrick|2003|p=84}} He breathed his last in 21 [[Tamil calendar|Vaikasi]] 1026.[[Malayalam Era|M.E]] His '' \u2018Sacred Golden Body\u2019 '' was interned at Poovandanthope which was now the [[Palliyarai]] of [[Swamithope Pathi]].{{fact|date=April 2018}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book |last=Vivekanandan |first=Siva |date=December 2003 |title=Ayya Vaikundar : Vazhvum Vazhibadum |publisher=Kavya |edition=1st |language=Tamil |trans-title=Ayya Vaikundar : Life and Worship }}\n* G. Patrick (2003), ''Religion and Subaltern Agency'', Department of Christian Studies, [[University of Madras]], [[Chennai]].\n* T. Krishnanathan (2000), ''Ayya Vaikundarin Vazhvum Sinthanaiyum'', [[Madurai Kamaraj University]], Thinai Publications, [[Nagercoil]].\n* C. Paulose (2002), ''Advaita Philosophy of Brahmasri Chattampi Swamikal'', Sree Sankaracharya University of Sanskrit, Ayya Vaikunta Nather Sidhasramam, Pothaiyadi.\n* R. Ponnu (2000), ''Sri Vaikunda Swamigal and Struggle for Social Equality in South India'', [[Madurai Kamaraj University]], Ram Publishers, [[Madurai]].\n* R. Ponnu (2002), ''Vaikunda Swamikal Ore Avataram'', Ram Publishers, Madurai.\n* R. Shunmugam (2001), ''Nadar Kulathil Narayanar Avataram'', Nadar Kuladeepam Publications, Karankadu.\n* Samuel Mateer (1871), ''The Land of charity: a descriptive account of Travancore and its people, Asian Educational Services'', {{ISBN|81-206-0319-2}}\n* V.T. Chellam (2002), ''Thamizaka Varalarum Panpadum'' (The History and Culture of Tamil Nadu), Manickavasakar Publications, Chennai.\n* [[Madanjeet Singh]] (2005), ''The Sasia Story'', France, {{ISBN|92-3-103992-X}}.\n* P. Sundaram Swamigal and K. Ponnumani (2001), ''Ayyavaikundanathar Jeevacharithram'' (Biography of Ayya Vaikunta Nathar), Ayyavaikuntanathar Siddasramam Publications, Pothaiyadi.\n* V. Nagam Aiya (1989), ''The Travancore State Manual'', Volume-2, [[Asian Educational Services]], {{ISBN|81-85499-33-0}}.\n* P. Sarvesvaran, ''Sri Vaikunda Swamikal \u2013 A Forgotten Social Reformer''.\n* N. Amalan (2000), ''Ayya Vaikundar Punitha Varalaru'', Akilam Publications, Swamithoppu.\n* Samuel Zecharia (1897), ''The London Missionary Society in South Travancore 1805\u20131855'', [[London Missionary Society|LMS]] Press, Nagercoil.\n* M. S. S. Pandiyan (1992)  ''Meanings of 'colonialism' and 'nationalism''': an essay on Vaikunda Swamy cult, Sage Publications\n* A. Sreedhara Menon (1967), ''A Survey of Kerala History'', D.C. Books, Kottayam, {{ISBN|81-264-1578-9}}\n* Dr. M. Immanuel (2007), ''Kanniyakumari: Aspects and Architects'', Historical Research & Publications Trust, Nagercoil, {{ISBN|978-81-901506-2-0}}\n\n==Citations==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Ayya Vaikundar]]\n", "name_user": "Dl2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "repair template; tidy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Historical_Vaikundar"}
{"title_page": "Nursultan Nazarbayev International Airport", "text_new": "{{short description|International airport in Nur-Sultan, Kazakhstan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name = Nursultan Nazarbayev International Airport\n| nativename = {{nowrap|{{nobold|{{lang|kk|Halyqaralyq Nursultan Nazarbaev \u00c1\u00fdeja\u0131y}}}}}}\n| image-width = \n| caption = \n| image = \n| image2 = Astana_SAM_0014_(15120297042).jpg\n| image2-width = 314\n| IATA = TSE\n| ICAO = UACC\n| WMO = 35188\n| LID = \u0410\u041a\u041b\n| type = Public\n| operator = JSC Astana International Airport\n| city-served = [[Nur-Sultan]], [[Akmola Region]]\n| location = [[Yesil District]], [[Nur-Sultan]], [[Kazakhstan]]\n| opened = {{start date and age|1931|12|01|}}\n| hub = * [[Air Astana]]\n| focus_city = \n* [[SCAT Airlines]]\n* [[FlyArystan]]\n* [[Qazaq Air]]\n| timezone = [[Time in Kazakhstan|ALMT]]\n| utc = [[UTC+06:00]]\n| elevation-m = 355\n| coordinates = {{coord|51|01|19|N|071|28|01|E|region:KZ|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map = Kazakhstan#Asia\n| pushpin_label ='''TSE'''/UACC\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in [[Yesil District]] , [[Nur-Sultan]] , [[Kazakhstan]]\n|image_map=\n|image_map_caption= [[Aeronautical Information Publication|AIP]] airport diagram as of November 2019\n| website = [http://nn-airport.kz/ nn-airport.kz]\n| metric-elev = Y\n| metric-rwy = Y\n| r1-number = 04/22\n| r1-length-m = 3,500\n| r1-surface = Asphalt\n| stat-year = 2019\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data = {{increase}} 5,099,391\n| stat2-header = Passenger change 18-19\n| stat2-data = {{increase}} 12.1%\n| footnotes = Sources: [http://www.astanaairport.kz/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=88&Itemid=295&lang=en Airport Statistics]<br />[[Aeronautical Information Publication|AIP]] Kazakhstan<ref name=\"AIP\">[https://archive.is/20130616030152/http://goszakup.ans.kz/AIP/AIRAC_AMDT_01_13/AIP/html/UA-frameset-en-KZ.html AIP Kazakhstan]</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Nursultan Nazarbayev International Airport''' {{airport codes|TSE|UACC}} ({{lang-kk|\u0425\u0430\u043b\u044b\u049b\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044b\u049b \u041d\u04b1\u0440\u0441\u04b1\u043b\u0442\u0430\u043d \u041d\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0440\u0431\u0430\u0435\u0432 \u04d8\u0443\u0435\u0436\u0430\u0439\u044b, Halyqaralyq Nursultan Nazarbaev \u00c1\u00fdeja\u0131y}}; until June 2017 ''Astana International Airport'') is an [[international airport]] in [[Akmola Region]], [[Kazakhstan]]. It is the primary [[international airport]] serving [[Nur-Sultan]]. The airport is the second-busiest international air passenger gateway into [[Central Asia]] (after [[Almaty International Airport]]), the [[List of the busiest airports in the former USSR|13th-busiest airport in the Post-Soviet states]], the [[List of the busiest airports in Kazakhstan|second-busiest airport in Kazakhstan]].\n\nNursultan Nazarbayev Airport is located in the [[Yesil District|Yesil]] administrative subdivision,{{Convert|16.7|km|abbr=on}} southeast of the capital city of [[Nur-Sultan]].\n\nThe airport features two passenger terminals and one runway. It serves as a hub for [[Air Astana]], and it is the primary operating base for [[SCAT Airlines]], [[FlyArystan]], [[Qazaq Air]]. Nursultan Nazarbayev Airport was also formerly a hub for Starlines Kazakhstan and Tselinograd OAO.\n\nThe facility opened in 1931 as '''Akmolinsk Airport''' and was renamed to as '''Tselinograd Airport''' (the airport's current [[IATA code]], '''TSE''', is derived from the city's previous name of [[Tselinograd]]) and was commonly known as '''Astana International Airport'''. With a government decree, the airport was renamed Nursultan Nazarbayev International Airport as a tribute to the first President.\n\n==History==\n=== Construction and early operations ===\n*'''1930:''' The airport was built 3 kilometers away from [[Akmolinsk]] (now \u2013 [[Nur-Sultan]]). There was a square field for aircraft take-off and landing, adobe 8-room station with a small waiting hall, a two-room house for pilots and fuel storage on the airport territory.\n*'''1931:''' The first airfield of [[Nur-Sultan]] (formerly [[Astana]]) was built in 1931 on the outskirts of the town and was developed further after [[World War II]]. There was a square field for aircraft take-off and landing, adobe 8-room station with a small waiting hall, a two-room house for pilots and fuel storage on the airport territory. The regular air traffic was established between [[Semipalatinsk]] and [[Akmolinsk]] (day of enterprise establishment). At the water flood period, the aerodrome was closed. Communication between aerodrome and city was by phone, ferry (there was no bridge over [[Ishim River]]), by foot path.. In the first few years the air traffic was ad-hoc by character, the timetables used to be as follows \u201caircraft departure on Monday morning\u201d or \u201con Wednesday at sunrise\u201d. Transportation of passengers, mail and cargo were carried out by aircraft: [[Kalinin K-4]], [[Kalinin K-5]], [[Polikarpov R-5]], [[Petlyakov Pe-2]].\n*'''1934:''' The regular flights were established, with the following routes:<br>1. [[Alma-Ata]] \u2013 [[Karaganda]] \u2013 [[Akmolinsk]] \u2013 [[Atbasar]] \u2013 [[Kostanay]] \u2013 [[Sverdlovsk, Russia|Sverdlovsk]].<br>2. [[Karaganda]] \u2013 [[Petropavl]]ovsk \u2013 [[Korgalzhyn]] \u2013 [[Akmolinsk]].\n\n=== After World War II ===\n*'''1946:''' In the beginning of 1946 the first group of [[Polikarpov Po-2]] aircraft arrived to [[Akmolinsk]] for regular service. The group belonged to Karaganda aviation enterprise. The following routes were opened for passenger and mail transportation: [[Akmolinsk]] \u2013 [[Korgalzhyn]] \u2013 [[Aksu, Kazakhstan|Aksu]] \u2013 [[Astrakhanka, Kazakhstan|Astrakhanka]] \u2013 [[Balkashino]] (settlements of [[Akmolinsk]] region). Operations division was organized consisting of 2 persons. In 1946 aviation began to render services for the national economy \u2013 medical aviation.\n*'''1947-1948:''' The fleet consisting of three [[Polikarpov Po-2]] aircraft was formed at the [[Akmolinsk]] airport base. This fleet was part of air group which was based in [[Karaganda]]. The airport was equipped with modern equipment (for that days), construction development has started: a Finnish house for radio station, three buildings and a garage were built. The total number of staff amounted to 40 \u2013 50 persons. The airport has begun servicing heavier types of aircraft [[Lisunov Li-2]] in addition to light aircraft.\n*'''1963:''' 04-th of November the airport of [[Tselinograd]] (formerly known as \u2013 [[Akmolinsk]]) accepted the first aircraft [[Ilyushin Il-18]] in new terminal, located 18&nbsp;km far from the city. Aircraft [[Ilyushin Il-18]] in new terminal, located 18&nbsp;km far from the city. On December, 1963 aircraft [[Ilyushin Il-18]] began to operate on regular flights. The airport terminal was at a building stage, therefore the adapted 2-storeyed building served as air terminal, where the Air traffic control service has been located\n*'''1966:''' 08-th of February the new air terminal was transferred into operation, and in June of the same year all services of united aviagroup relocated to the new airport.\n*'''1969:''' the aircraft park of [[Tselinograd]] aviagroup has replenished with the first aircraft [[Antonov An-24]]. With reception of aircraft [[Antonov An-24]] the volume of passenger, mail, and cargo transportation has sharply increased. People began to fly to many cities of the former Union on own airpark.\n*'''1975:''' The aircraft [[Tupolev Tu-154]] has firstly landed on our runway. Since this moment regular flight by aircraft [[Tupolev Tu-154]] on [[Alma-Ata]] \u2013 [[Tselinograd]] \u2013 [[Moscow]] route and back has been opened.\n*'''1998:''' historical mark for [[Akmola]] ([[Nur-Sultan]]) aviators was the change of the capital. Airdrome reconstruction begun and finished in a relatively short time: the runway with artificial covering was extended for about 3500 meters; taxiway and apron were also expanded. Replacements of light system and the radio navigating equipment; the VIP building was constructed, the airport complex was reconstructed.\n\n=== Development since the 2000s ===\n*'''2005:''' A large-scale international airport reconstruction project has been completed. On February 2, 2005, the grand opening of the new passenger terminal of the airport took place. The terminal area was more than 25 thousand square meters. meters. Number of check-in counters - 24, 2 luggage straps. Currently, the terminal is used to service domestic flights and is called Terminal 2.\n*'''2014:''' The beginning of the implementation of the projects \"Reconstruction of the passenger terminal of JSC \"Astana International Airport\", as well as \"Construction of the Business Aviation Terminal\".\n*'''2015:''' The grand opening of the business aviation terminal took place on November 19, 2015. The BAT area is 2,400 square meters, the capacity is 200 passengers per hour. The terminal building housed a lounge bar, a conference hall, rooms for negotiations, convenience for passengers with children, a duty-free shop, there are 52 parking spaces for guests.\n*'''2017:''' Within the framework of Infrastructure Development Program a new passenger terminal for international flights was built. 47,000 sq. M. The new terminal adds 6 new aircraft parking lots with landing sleeves and 4 bus landing routes to the airport infrastructure, and also includes a variety of technologies and processes designed to improve the quality of service at the airport.\n\nCurrently, Nursultan Nazarbayev International Airport has the category of the International Civil Aviation Association - IIIA, as well as accepts and serves aircraft of all types, with no takeoff weight limitation - [[Ilyushin Il-76]], [[Antonov An-124 Ruslan]], [[Boeing 747-400F]].\n\n==Terminals==\n{| class=\"infobox bordered vcard\" style=\"width:350px; font-size:80%; line-height:160%;\"\n!colspan=\"3\" style=\"background-color:#4682B4; color:white; line-height:180%;\" |Passenger terminal buildings\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"lightgrey\"|<small>Total</small>\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|<small>Opened</small>\n|colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"|<small>{{start date and age|1931|12|1|}}</small>\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|<small>Floor area</small>\n|colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"|<small>70 892 m2</small>\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|<small>Handling capacity </small>\n|colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"|<small>8 200 000</small>\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|<small>Parking bays</small>\n|colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"|<small>12 (aerobridge)<br>92 (remote)</small>\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"lightgrey\"|<small>T1 \u2013 International Terminal</small>\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|<small>Opened</small>\n|colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"|<small>{{start date and age|2017|05|31|}}</small>\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|<small>Floor area</small>\n|colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"|<small>47 000 m2</small>\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|<small>Handling capacity </small>\n|colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"|<small>5 200 000</small>\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|<small>Parking bays</small>\n|colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"|<small> 6 (aerobridge)<br> 4 (remote)</small>\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"lightgrey\"|<small>T2 \u2013 Domestic Terminal</small>\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|<small>Opened</small>\n|colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"|<small>{{start date and age|2005|2|2|}}</small>\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|<small>Floor area</small>\n|colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"|<small>23 892 m2 </small>\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|<small> Handling capacity  </small>\n|colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"|<small>3 000 000</small>\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|<small>Parking bays</small>\n|colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"|<small> 6 (aerobridge)<br> 4 (remote)</small>\n|-\n|}\n\nThere are separate terminal buildings for domestic and international flights. Both terminals are adjacent, share a single car park and have a connecting corridor for transit passengers.\n\n=== T1 \u2013 International Terminal ===\nThe new international terminal (labelled \"T1\") opened in June 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Astana International Airport's new terminal takes the first international flight|url=http://caan.asia/en/show-astana_international_airport%E2%80%99s__new_terminal_takes_the_first_international_flight.html|website=Central Asia Aero News|accessdate=12 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170812134849/http://caan.asia/en/show-astana_international_airport%E2%80%99s__new_terminal_takes_the_first_international_flight.html|archive-date=12 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Plans for the new terminal show 5\u20136 new departure gates complementing the gates in the previously existing terminal building.<ref>{{cite web|title=Astana International Airport Kazakhstan|url=http://www.mabetex.com/en/78/astana-international-airport-kazakhstan-p.html|website=Mabetex|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nWithin the framework of Infrastructure Development Program \"Nurly Zhol\" a new passenger terminal for international flights was built. 47,000 sq. M. The new terminal adds 6 new aircraft parking lots with landing sleeves and 4 bus landing routes to the Airport infrastructure, and also includes a variety of technologies and processes designed to improve the quality of service at the Airport. The new terminal has a public catering area of 1000 square meters, retail outlets occupy 1,300 square meters.\n\n=== T2 \u2013 Domestic Terminal ===\nWith the opening of the new international terminal, the old terminal (now labelled \"T2\") is now dedicated to domestic flights. On February 2, 2005, the grand opening of the T2 passenger terminal of the airport took place. The terminal area was more than 25 thousand square meters. meters. Number of check-in counters - 24, 2 luggage straps.\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n\n===Passenger===\nAll flights are cancelled due to [[COVID-19]].\n<!-- WHEN ADDING A NEW ROUTE, OR ADDING AN END DATE FOR A ROUTE PLEASE ADD A REFERENCE, ALSO ADD THE ROUTE AND LINK ON THE CORRESPONDING AIRPORTS ARTICLE AND THE AIRLINES ARTICLE IF IT IS A NEW DESTINATION, ANYTHING WHICH IS NOT REFERENCED WILL BE REMOVED. ALSO WHEN ADDING A NEW ROUTE, A FIRM DATE IS MANDATORY. PLEASE HAVE RESPECT FOR THE FACTUAL ACCURACY OF THIS PAGE. -->\nThe following airlines operate regular scheduled and charter services to and from Nur-Sultan:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nn-airport.kz/flight-status|title= Nursultan Nazarbayev International Airport Flight Schedule|accessdate=23 November 2019}}</ref>\n{{Airport destination list | 3rdcoltitle = {{Abbr|Refs.|References}} | 3rdcolunsortable=yes\n<!-- -->\n| [[Aeroflot]] | [[Sheremetyevo International Airport|Moscow\u2013Sheremetyevo]] |<ref>{{cite web|title=Online timetable |website=Aeroflot|url=http://onlineboard.aeroflot.ru/en|accessdate=August 5, 2018}}</ref>\n<!-- -->\n| [[Air Astana]] | [[Aktau Airport|Aktau]], [[Aktobe Airport|Aktobe]], [[Almaty International Airport|Almaty]], [[Atyrau Airport|Atyrau]], [[Heydar Aliyev International Airport|Baku]], [[Beijing Capital International Airport|Beijing\u2013Capital]], [[Dubai International Airport|Dubai\u2013International]], [[Frankfurt Airport|Frankfurt]], [[Istanbul Airport|Istanbul]], [[Kazan Airport|Kazan]] (resumes 2 June 2020),<ref>{{cite news |last1= |first1= |title=The Nur-Sultan \u2013 Kazan Route Returns|url=https://airastana.com/kaz/en-us/Plan/Special-Offers/Astana-Kazan|accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=FlyArystan}}</ref> [[Boryspil International Airport|Kyiv\u2013Boryspil]], [[Kyzylorda Airport|Kyzylorda]], [[Heathrow Airport|London\u2013Heathrow]], [[Moscow Domodedovo Airport|Moscow\u2013Domodedovo]], [[Tolmachevo Airport|Novosibirsk]], [[Omsk Tsentralny Airport|Omsk]], [[Oral Ak Zhol Airport|Oral]], [[Oskemen Airport|Oskemen]], [[Charles de Gaulle Airport|Paris\u2013Charles de Gaulle]] (ends 31 May 2020),<ref>https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/287805/air-astana-discontinues-nur-sultan-paris-cdg-service-in-late-may-2020/</ref> [[Pulkovo Airport|Saint Petersburg]], [[Incheon International Airport|Seoul\u2013Incheon]], [[Shymkent Airport|Shymkent]], [[Tashkent Airport|Tashkent]], [[Shota Rustaveli Tbilisi International Airport|Tbilisi]], [[\u00dcr\u00fcmqi Diwopu International Airport|Urumqi]], [[Koltsovo Airport|Yekaterinburg]] <br>'''Seasonal:''' [[Antalya Airport|Antalya]]<br>'''Charter:''' [[Sharm El Sheikh International Airport|Sharm El Sheikh]]<br>'''Seasonal charter:''' [[Bodrum Airport|Bodrum]] (begins 4 June 2020),<ref>{{cite news |last1= |first1= |title=Air Astana to operate two Bodrum charters in summer 2020|url=https://centreforaviation.com/news/air-astana-to-operate-two-bodrum-charters-in-summer-2020-977012|accessdate=19 February 2020 |work=CAPA |date=19 February 2020}}</ref> [[Kittil\u00e4 Airport|Kittila]]|<ref>{{cite web|title=Online timetable |website=Air Astana|url=https://airastana.com/global/en-us/Plan/Flight-Information/Timetable|accessdate=November 25, 2019}}</ref>\n<!-- -->\n| [[Air Astana]]<br />{{nowrap|operated by [[FlyArystan]]}} |[[Aktobe Airport|Aktobe]], [[Almaty International Airport|Almaty]], [[Kostanay Airport|Kostanay]], [[Kyzylorda Airport|Kyzylorda]], [[Zhukovsky International Airport|Moscow\u2013Zhukovsky]], [[Pavlodar Airport|Pavlodar]], [[Petropavl Airport|Petropavl]], [[Semey Airport|Semey]], [[Shymkent Airport|Shymkent]], [[Taraz Airport|Taraz]] |<ref>{{cite web|title=Online Timetable |website=FlyArystan|url=https://booking.flyarystan.com/web/FlightSchedule.xhtml|accessdate=November 25, 2019}}</ref>\n<!-- -->\n| [[Air China]] | [[Beijing Capital International Airport|Beijing\u2013Capital]] |<ref>{{cite web|title=Onlin